WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.480
Hi, my name is Sophie Beiers. Thank you for watching my video. I'm super honored to be

00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:16.840
a part of this conference. I definitely wish that we could all be in person. But in the

00:00:16.840 --> 00:00:21.959
meantime, welcome to my kitchen. I'm excited to talk to you a little bit about my process

00:00:21.959 --> 00:00:27.400
in creating data visualizations and data driven stories at the ACLU. So just a little bit

00:00:27.400 --> 00:00:32.360
about me. I'm a data journalist at the ACLU where I analyze data for our lawyers' legal

00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:37.799
arguments and visualize and report on our data for external advocacy purposes. I'm only

00:00:37.799 --> 00:00:44.720
a few years into being a part of the R community, so I'm really excited to be here. So to start,

00:00:44.720 --> 00:00:50.040
what is data science and data journalism more broadly at the ACLU? Some of you might know

00:00:50.040 --> 00:00:56.200
and remember Brooke Matabuanwu, who spoke at the 2019 RStudio conference about her data

00:00:56.200 --> 00:00:59.880
work in helping reunify children that were separated from their families while seeking

00:00:59.880 --> 00:01:05.360
refuge in our country. She happens to be my awesome manager and colleague, and I felt

00:01:05.360 --> 00:01:10.599
she recently summed up our work in just one slack that reads, the lawyer called our analysis

00:01:10.599 --> 00:01:17.239
both deeply disturbing and extremely helpful, which might just be the slogan for our team.

00:01:17.239 --> 00:01:22.519
This leads me to an important word to define, terribulous, which is commonly used on our

00:01:22.519 --> 00:01:27.680
team as a way of expressing excitement over being able to prove usually terrible news

00:01:27.680 --> 00:01:33.120
with quantitative evidence. Our analysis of the data that we receive often uncovers disparities

00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:39.000
that hold up in court and help our lawyers win their legal arguments. But in all seriousness,

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.440
what this often means is the data that we are privileged to analyze represent real human

00:01:43.440 --> 00:01:49.120
beings who are being harmed in one way or another. I'll briefly share with you a few

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:56.160
examples of what this might mean. For example, each row in this data was a person that was

00:01:56.160 --> 00:02:01.160
filed for eviction. We found in this case that filings for eviction impacted black women

00:02:01.160 --> 00:02:07.360
at alarmingly disproportionate rates. Another example is this recent report that we put

00:02:07.360 --> 00:02:12.279
out where we found that black people, despite using marijuana at the same rates as white

00:02:12.279 --> 00:02:19.000
people, are still being disproportionately arrested for possession of marijuana. We

00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:23.600
also found that people of color were more likely to have their driver's licenses suspended

00:02:23.600 --> 00:02:28.399
due to unpaid and often unaffordable fines and fees. And we were able to visualize the

00:02:28.399 --> 00:02:33.520
story of two black women whose lives were turned upside down without the ability to

00:02:33.520 --> 00:02:41.500
use their cars. All in all, I've been really lucky to be a part of these and other data

00:02:41.500 --> 00:02:45.699
journalistic projects during my time at the ACLU. So I wanted to talk to you a little

00:02:45.699 --> 00:02:51.220
bit about the process that I often go through and the key steps I take in creating my data

00:02:51.220 --> 00:02:56.860
visualizations. This will include the feedback that I sometimes receive, what I've done or

00:02:56.860 --> 00:03:01.660
not done with that feedback, and other considerations that I think are important in getting to a

00:03:01.660 --> 00:03:08.779
final result. So some of you might be thinking that it's just this easy. You go from data

00:03:08.779 --> 00:03:14.300
analysis to visualization, you're good, you have a great viz, and you can go on and just

00:03:14.300 --> 00:03:19.699
enjoy your weekend. Maybe even I thought that at one point, based on this flack evidence,

00:03:19.699 --> 00:03:24.580
when I was analyzing data a few months into the pandemic and came to the conclusion that

00:03:24.580 --> 00:03:30.940
actually letting incarcerated people out of jails had no effect on crime levels nearby.

00:03:30.940 --> 00:03:38.580
Spoiler, this is not the process, but it was the finding. The actual process in my experience

00:03:38.580 --> 00:03:43.339
can be really messy and definitely not linear. But I'll share with you the key elements and

00:03:43.339 --> 00:03:47.220
considerations to take that I believe have set me up for a success for projects like

00:03:47.220 --> 00:03:55.259
this. First, you'll get some data. A lot of the time for us here, that means that a lawyer

00:03:55.259 --> 00:03:59.619
will have some kind of data that they've obtained through the discovery process or through a

00:03:59.619 --> 00:04:06.699
FOIA request, and a lot of times we'll just use publicly available data. Next, you'll

00:04:06.699 --> 00:04:12.300
use R to read and explore that data. During the exploration process, I use the tidyverse

00:04:12.300 --> 00:04:17.779
quite a bit, but also the janitor package is one of my favorites to make easy tables,

00:04:17.779 --> 00:04:25.100
and always ggplot2 to find quick trends and actually start visualizing my findings.

00:04:25.100 --> 00:04:29.059
So this is important. By now, you'll want to start thinking about what are your main

00:04:29.059 --> 00:04:33.899
points that you found in your exploration that you want to visualize and make clear.

00:04:33.899 --> 00:04:40.859
Ask yourself, does my visualization support and highlight my main point? You'll also want

00:04:40.859 --> 00:04:45.739
to carefully consider your audience. Is your audience made of purely academics? Are they

00:04:45.739 --> 00:04:49.820
advocates? Are they people who know a lot about your topic already, or maybe they know

00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:56.980
nothing at all? It's also good to ask for feedback on your visualizations from various

00:04:56.980 --> 00:05:01.980
people. You'll want to be specific about the main points that you're trying to visualize

00:05:01.980 --> 00:05:07.100
before receiving feedback about whether those main points are coming through clearly or not to those people.

00:05:07.100 --> 00:05:14.100
And then you might find that once you receive feedback, you'll start iterating on your

00:05:14.100 --> 00:05:18.100
database, which means you'll likely need to go kind of back and forth and check a lot

00:05:18.100 --> 00:05:26.779
of these boxes again. The process could end up looking a lot like this. Now, to show you

00:05:26.779 --> 00:05:30.700
how I've gone about using this process in practice, I'll go through these steps once

00:05:30.700 --> 00:05:38.019
more with a real-life example. For the purposes of the example that I'll use, I'll need to

00:05:38.019 --> 00:05:42.700
start with a little bit of background on this recent project that our team worked on. Sometime

00:05:42.700 --> 00:05:48.380
into the very beginning of the COVID-19 pandemic, it became really clear that people in jails

00:05:48.380 --> 00:05:54.260
and people that were incarcerated in America, which, by the way, has the highest incarceration

00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:59.739
rate in the world in particular, would be at risk. Incarcerated people are subject to

00:05:59.739 --> 00:06:05.619
extreme overcrowding, and jails often lack the resources and facilities that allow for

00:06:05.619 --> 00:06:11.980
handwashing and other hygienic practices that are necessary to slow the spread of COVID-19.

00:06:11.980 --> 00:06:16.459
So it was really clear that in order to save lives, action had to be taken, and it had

00:06:16.459 --> 00:06:21.459
to be taken quickly. Our team partnered with academic researchers to build a model that

00:06:21.459 --> 00:06:27.179
accounted for the dynamics of the jail system and estimated the additional illnesses and

00:06:27.179 --> 00:06:32.739
loss of life that we'd expect if none of these preventative measures were taken. We

00:06:32.739 --> 00:06:38.299
recommended reducing arrests such that people were only being arrested for the most serious

00:06:38.299 --> 00:06:44.700
incidents and promptly releasing people who were pre-trial or charged for low-level crimes

00:06:44.700 --> 00:06:51.540
or were particularly vulnerable to the disease and posed no risk of immediate threat to others.

00:06:51.540 --> 00:06:55.779
All in all, the team estimated that taking these precautions could save 100,000 human

00:06:55.779 --> 00:07:01.579
lives, both inside the jails and in their surrounding communities. Many communities

00:07:01.579 --> 00:07:06.859
did begin prioritizing the lives of incarcerated people and the people who worked within jails.

00:07:06.859 --> 00:07:11.220
Some localities reduced low-level arrests, or set bond at zero, or released a subset

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:16.579
of incarcerated people. But there was some backlash. Some people were worried that taking

00:07:16.579 --> 00:07:21.019
these actions would result in a huge spike in crime in the surrounding communities, despite

00:07:21.019 --> 00:07:25.899
research showing that in New York City, for instance, people released from jails due to

00:07:25.899 --> 00:07:32.339
COVID were rearrested at lower rates than even expected. To quell these concerns further,

00:07:32.339 --> 00:07:36.739
our team analyzed trends in reported crimes during the initial three months of the pandemic

00:07:36.739 --> 00:07:42.339
in 29 of the largest US cities where data was available and released this report with

00:07:42.339 --> 00:07:47.940
our findings. For the purposes of this project, our goal was to find whether there was any

00:07:47.940 --> 00:07:53.700
relationship between the change in county jail populations and the reported crime rate

00:07:53.700 --> 00:08:01.000
in the closest metropolitan area. So, back to the process, starting with the data step.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:05.660
We needed two categories of data, one for county jail populations and one that showed

00:08:05.660 --> 00:08:11.100
the number of crimes reported in the nearest city. These were ultimately the 29 locations

00:08:11.100 --> 00:08:16.059
for which I could find quality reported crime data for, for the time periods necessary that

00:08:16.059 --> 00:08:22.579
were either aggregated daily, weekly, or monthly for all of 2019 through May 2020 that we could

00:08:22.579 --> 00:08:28.100
also find jail population information for. So, we needed both. We collected this data

00:08:28.100 --> 00:08:32.900
a bit in piecemeal, mainly through Googling for specific county sheriff's offices or finding

00:08:32.900 --> 00:08:38.859
public open data sets. We ended up downloading countless CSVs and Excel files and even PDFs

00:08:38.859 --> 00:08:44.460
kind of continuously whenever we noticed a bit, a new bit of data had dropped. Hence,

00:08:44.460 --> 00:08:50.179
the circular arrow around the data step. We also used the Vera Institute's data that

00:08:50.179 --> 00:08:55.539
tracked the number of people in each county jail over time and we ended up using the specific

00:08:55.539 --> 00:09:02.219
dates of February 29th and April 30th to calculate the percent change in jail population. Because

00:09:02.219 --> 00:09:06.880
most jails took action early on in the pandemic, we looked at the crime rates during the time

00:09:06.880 --> 00:09:13.619
period of March through May 2019 and compared those to the same time period in 2020. And

00:09:13.619 --> 00:09:18.140
then to sort of standardize the way that we analyzed crime, and also because many of

00:09:18.140 --> 00:09:22.460
these cities' crime data sets only included these types of crimes, we focused on part

00:09:22.460 --> 00:09:27.780
one crimes, which are defined by the Uniform Crime Reporting Program, and they encompass

00:09:27.780 --> 00:09:33.260
the most frequently reported violent and property crimes. You'll see that data exploration here

00:09:33.260 --> 00:09:39.299
was super messy for me. This is an example of what I saw using this function for my very

00:09:39.299 --> 00:09:47.859
favorite janitor package on the crime description column in just one city. During my exploration,

00:09:47.859 --> 00:09:54.900
I created this plot in R, which showed the relationship between the magnitude of the

00:09:54.900 --> 00:10:00.020
change in jail population and the magnitude of the change in crime during that same time

00:10:00.020 --> 00:10:05.340
frame. Now, it could be really tempting to draw a regression line and to try and focus

00:10:05.340 --> 00:10:11.340
on some type of significant correlation that just isn't there. I received feedback from

00:10:11.340 --> 00:10:15.820
my colleagues that this graph focused a little bit too much on sort of the outliers, which

00:10:15.820 --> 00:10:20.700
were one location that increased their jail population, and one location where there was

00:10:20.700 --> 00:10:25.940
more reported crime than in the previous year. It was then I realized that one of the most

00:10:25.940 --> 00:10:29.500
important main points that I could make was actually the lack of relationship between

00:10:29.500 --> 00:10:36.900
X and Y. So after lots of data cleaning and trying out more charts and receiving more

00:10:36.900 --> 00:10:41.820
feedback, these were the three main points that I wanted to make clear in my report and

00:10:41.820 --> 00:10:47.580
visualize to my audience. One, crime was not on the rise compared to the same time period

00:10:47.580 --> 00:10:54.859
the year prior. Crime rates were instead right within normal range or even lower. Second,

00:10:54.859 --> 00:10:59.260
most of the locales that we found data for did decrease their jail populations during

00:10:59.260 --> 00:11:04.299
this time period. And like I said before, just one location actually increased its population.

00:11:04.299 --> 00:11:10.460
Lastly, and importantly, we found no relationship between the county jail population and its

00:11:10.460 --> 00:11:16.700
increase or decrease and the number of crimes that were reported. So once I decided on these

00:11:16.700 --> 00:11:20.979
main points, it was time to come up with a few mock-ups of graphs that I thought would

00:11:20.979 --> 00:11:26.299
clearly express these. Of course, though, this is not always easy, especially when you

00:11:26.299 --> 00:11:31.539
realize that you need to take your audience into consideration. So unfortunately, this

00:11:31.539 --> 00:11:36.219
is an example of a time where I thought I nailed it, I'd come to the perfect solution,

00:11:36.219 --> 00:11:42.260
but I hadn't yet considered our audience. So this is a graph that shows the 29 locations

00:11:42.260 --> 00:11:47.500
in order of the percent change in jail population. The gray bar indicates the range of monthly

00:11:47.500 --> 00:11:53.179
crimes between January 2018 and February 2020, and the three dots indicate the number

00:11:53.179 --> 00:11:58.059
of monthly crimes reported in March, April, and May of 2020. You'll see that a lot of

00:11:58.059 --> 00:12:02.859
the time. The three dots are to the left of the gray bar, but never are they to the right

00:12:02.859 --> 00:12:07.260
of the gray bar, which indicates that reported crime during these first few months of the

00:12:07.260 --> 00:12:14.460
pandemic were within normal or expected range or lower. I will give credit to Lucia, our

00:12:14.460 --> 00:12:19.059
chief analytics officer, for scribbling down this idea in Slack, of course, but will give

00:12:19.059 --> 00:12:25.419
credit to myself for what I felt was kind of incredible execution. The team of data

00:12:25.419 --> 00:12:32.780
scientists, of course, loved it. I thought I was basically done. But let's remember,

00:12:32.780 --> 00:12:37.820
your audience is key. So the next day, I received the following feedback from several non-analytics

00:12:37.820 --> 00:12:44.700
folks. It honestly was a little bit like reading my own bad reviews, but it's important

00:12:44.700 --> 00:12:49.500
not to look at constructive feedback that way. These colleagues were speaking up about

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:55.900
some major issues with this graph. You might agree. I agree now. They were right. I see

00:12:55.900 --> 00:13:02.140
feedback that's qualified with things like, I'm not a numbers person. A lot. People sometimes

00:13:02.140 --> 00:13:07.219
blame themselves for not knowing how to interpret a data viz, but it's actually really our job

00:13:07.219 --> 00:13:12.260
to make sure that the viz works for them and works for our audience. So this crimes

00:13:12.260 --> 00:13:16.900
and decarceration report was not just for data scientists. It was for a far more general

00:13:16.900 --> 00:13:23.059
audience, and this chart was clearly not working. So sometimes this means going back to the

00:13:23.059 --> 00:13:28.059
drawing board, doing a little bit more data exploration, always with the janitor and ggplot

00:13:28.059 --> 00:13:33.700
packages for me, and trying out sort of new ways of visualizing your main points while

00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:39.380
thinking about your audience. These charts were hashtag innoventive, but they simply

00:13:39.380 --> 00:13:43.700
weren't working. Some of the most valuable feedback conversations I had were not over

00:13:43.700 --> 00:13:47.780
Slack, so I have no hard evidence, but in the times that you're asking for feedback

00:13:47.780 --> 00:13:52.419
from someone, it's really important to ask the why behind something isn't working for

00:13:52.419 --> 00:13:59.940
them. Sometimes the why might be sort of surprising, or maybe it'll make you actually realize that

00:13:59.940 --> 00:14:04.219
what you need to do is add better annotating, rather than just scrapping the whole thing

00:14:04.219 --> 00:14:11.179
and starting over. And in the spirit of reiterating that this process was one messy adventure,

00:14:11.179 --> 00:14:15.979
before showing you the final visualizations we ended up with, at the end of the day, I

00:14:15.979 --> 00:14:20.580
really feel like this quote just kind of drives it all home.

00:14:20.580 --> 00:14:25.340
So these were the final graphics that we published on our site. Both were created in R and touched

00:14:25.340 --> 00:14:30.340
up in Illustrator. Both, I feel, do a good job of expressing our three main points, and

00:14:30.340 --> 00:14:36.659
are not just interpretable for quote numbers people. I know these are probably a little

00:14:36.659 --> 00:14:41.539
bit hard to see, so I'll share a link to my report in my presentation, as well as where

00:14:41.539 --> 00:14:45.780
you can find the R code for the analysis in Viz.

00:14:45.780 --> 00:14:51.340
And one last wrench I'll throw at you, because it was thrown at me, was that it turns out

00:14:51.340 --> 00:14:55.219
police data is often dynamic, meaning that sometimes crimes that occurred actually maybe

00:14:55.219 --> 00:15:00.380
a month ago could have been reported today. I cannot stress enough how much of a lifesaver

00:15:00.380 --> 00:15:05.299
reusable code in R was throughout this process, given the amount of extremely last minute

00:15:05.299 --> 00:15:11.380
data dumps and sort of changing out CSV files here and there. We want it to be precise,

00:15:11.380 --> 00:15:17.580
and it's thanks to R that remaking these graphs time and time again was such a small deal.

00:15:17.580 --> 00:15:22.659
So hopefully through this process, I've been able to convince you that data Viz is and

00:15:22.659 --> 00:15:27.419
should often be non-linear. Mentors in my life have taught me that being good at making

00:15:27.419 --> 00:15:32.179
effective visualizations is not about getting from point A to point B the quickest. It's

00:15:32.179 --> 00:15:36.219
actually about carefully considering each of these points that makes you an effective

00:15:36.219 --> 00:15:39.340
communicator to your audience.

00:15:39.340 --> 00:15:45.140
Lastly, feel free to reach out to me if you have any questions or just want to nerd out

00:15:45.140 --> 00:15:47.780
about data Viz. And thank you.

